# Living Documentation

After every substantive implementation step (new feature, architecture change, bug fix, discovered constraint), update the relevant project docs **in the same response** — do not wait to be asked.

## What to Update

- **`.cursor/rules/*.mdc`** — Add or revise rules when you discover new conventions, constraints, or API gotchas that future prompts should know about.
- **`.cursor/docs/*.md`** — Add or revise deep-reference docs when you learn new internals (e.g. CloudCannon API behaviour, edge cases, data structures).
- **`README.md`** — Keep the user-facing docs in sync with reality. Update the "How It Works" section, data attributes table, and any code examples when the implementation changes.
- **`.cursor/rules/rcc-v2-mission.mdc`** — Update the mission/status summary when the high-level approach shifts (e.g. from clone-and-replace to live API).

## When to Update

- You just changed how a feature works (update README + mission rule)
- You discovered an API quirk or constraint (add to a docs file or rule)
- You added/removed a data attribute, config option, or CLI flag (update README)
- You refactored file structure (update codebase map rule)

## How to Update

- Keep updates concise — match the style of the existing file.
- Prefer editing existing sections over adding new ones.
- Do not bloat docs with implementation minutiae; focus on things that help a future reader (human or AI) understand the system quickly.
